## .NET 8 Migration: `TimedExecutor`

### Key Breaking Changes

1. **`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** — removed entirely in .NET Core+
2. **`Thread.ResetAbort()` also removed** — no longer needed
3. **`ThreadAbortException` is never thrown** by the runtime

### The Fix: Use `Task` + `CancellationToken`

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Block until completion or timeout — mirrors original semantics
            task.Wait(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }

        // Task.Result unwraps AggregateException for faulted tasks,
        // but .Wait() above already threw if faulted — this is safe.
        return task.Result;
    }

    // Async overload (preferred in modern code)
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<CancellationToken, Task<T>> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            return await work(cts.Token).WaitAsync(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### Critical Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **No forced kill** | Unlike `Thread.Abort()`, cancellation is *cooperative* — the `work` delegate **must** check `ct.IsCancellationRequested` or pass `ct` to I/O calls, otherwise it runs forever in the background. |
| **Signature change** | Callers must update from `Func<T>` to `Func<CancellationToken, T>`. |
| **Fire-and-forget leak** | If `work` ignores the token, the `Task` keeps running after timeout. Consider logging or tracking orphaned tasks. |
| **`Task.Wait()` wraps in `AggregateException`** | The original code threw `AggregateException` explicitly — `Task.Wait()` does this automatically for faulted tasks, so behavior is preserved. |

### Caller Migration

```csharp
// BEFORE (.NET Framework)
var executor = new TimedExecutor();
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    () => SlowComputation(),
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));

// AFTER (.NET 8) — work must honor the token
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    ct =>
    {
        // Check token in loops / pass to async APIs
        for (int i = 0; i < 1_000_000; i++)
        {
            ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
            // ... work ...
        }
        return ComputeResult();
    },
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
```

The fundamental shift: .NET 8 uses **cooperative cancellation** instead of **thread abortion**. Your work delegates must participate by checking the `CancellationToken` — there is no equivalent to the old "kill the thread" behavior.
